2Ô∏è‚É£ What is an Anonymous Class?

‚úÖ An anonymous class is a class without a name.
Used when you need a one-time implementation of a class or interface.
Usually used for event handling, threads, or simple interfaces.

üî∏ Example:
interface Greeting {
    void sayHello();
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Greeting g = new Greeting() { // Anonymous class
            public void sayHello() {
                System.out.println("Hello from Anonymous Class");
            }
        };
        g.sayHello();
    }
}


Output:

Hello from Anonymous Class


‚úÖ Key points:

No class name.

Usually instantiated in place.

Can extend a class or implement an interface.

Used for quick, one-time usage.

